description.narrative: (Tanzania): The LCWT activity will use FY 2020 funds to reduce threats to chimpanzees and their habitat in the Kigoma and Katavi regions. LCWT will achieve this by supporting the regional and district authorities to develop and implement a strategic landscape-level plan for conservation. The activity will provide technical assistance to communities and local government authorities to develop and implement inclusive land-use plans and district land-use frameworks that promote conservation and forest restoration in critical chimpanzee habitats outside of protected areas. The activity will also support the management of the Gombe-Masato-Ugalla UNESCO Biosphere Reserve and provide technical assistance to districts developing the management plans for two newly gazetted local authority forest reserves - Tongue west and Masato. The program includes a reproductive health/family planning component that will lead demand creation campaigns and support family planning services in four districts of Kigoma and Katavi. The primary threats to the biodiversity and remaining forest habitat in the western Tanzanian landscape are the direct results of a rapidly growing local population and its continued reliance on natural resources and unsustainable land-use practices. In partnership with local leaders and communities, the activity will conduct social and behavior change interventions that promote healthier families, effective natural resource management, and train communities to diversify livelihoods as part of an effort to reduce pressure on natural resources. These interventions help further Tanzania's journey to self-reliance by developing the country's own ability to monitor, preserve, and benefit from its natural resources...... .
